I've never reviewed a recipe before, but this beef stew was ridiculously great. Everyone in my family from my 87 year old dad, to my 31 year old daughter couldn't get enough of it. I made the full 5 pounds and followed the recipe exactly...except I didn't strain the brown veggies. For anyone who worries about adding balsamic vinegar...just use the good stuff. Not the great $40 a bottle vinegar...but not the cheap salad dressing vinegar either. A nice sweet, starting to thicken balsamic vinegar is perfect! I didn't dredge the meat and the sauce was perfect. I used the full bottle of wine, with the beef stock and the water and there was plenty of gravy. I'll be making another 5 pounds at my kids' request so they can have some in the freezer at all times. Man, this was yummy!

Rating: 4
I've now made this recipe twice with success. While the recipe is labor intensive and takes time, the end product is worth it - a very hearty and tasty beef stew that rivals any I've had in the past. Some things I've learned: 1. Keep a can (14oz) of beef broth or two for later - one for after braising stew and separating out meat and then for reheating next day. There just doesn't seem to be enough broth to cook added carrots and potatoes. Also, add a bouillon cube for more flavor. 2. After straining, remove all meat and then press solids for extra liquid. With remaining solids, remove thyme sprigs and bay leaves, press garlic paste from cloves, add some to meat and broth in the pot and then puree the remaining carrots, celery, onions and other garlic leftover and add to broth containing meat and new carrots and potatoes. Then, add about a cup of water and stir before simmering for about an hour to cook new vegetables thoroughly. Frozen peas are a nice touch. 3. If you can, buy the stew meat already trimmed and cut into pieces. For the extra $1 or so a pound, it's well worth the time savings. 3. For wine, use Crane Lake Pinot Noir. It's 4.99/bottle. Finally, do this on a weekend day and start in the morning.

