Rating: 3
Previous reviewer, Ms. Donnelly, makes a good point; this a good BASIC recipe from which to work from in order to reach stew nirvana. However, just a couple of simple adjustments will transform this recipe into a true winner. The recipe excels in establishing some base flavor components with the wine, tomato paste, and balsamic (please, do NOT skip these). It, however, lacks spice, using just a bit of thyme and bay leaves to flavor 5 pounds of meat and over 4 pounds of vegetables!?! Preposterous! My adjustment for this recipe was as simple as seasoning both meat and vegetables before they were sauteed. I chose a North-African flavor profile and made a spice blend with 2T oregano, 1T cumin, 1T coriander, 2t cinnamon. Play with any combination of spices that sound attractive to you. Be bold and generous. In regards to the "watery" issue other reviewers address, simply hold back on the water and broth. Add enough to liquid to just cover the ingredients before it goes into the oven. You can always add more later, as necessary. Also, I found no need to go through the tedious process of separating the meat from the original batch of vegetables. I had originally cut them small enough, so that they dissolved into the stewy gunk. Good luck, and happy tweaking!

Rating: 2
I've been testing many stew recipes this past year trying to find my one "go to" stew recipe that stands above all others. This recipe is perfectly acceptable, but it's not the standout recipe for which I am looking. I do really like the flavor the balsamic adds. However at the end of the day this stew is a bit too soupy, and the depth of flavor I'm looking for just isn't quite there. The meat is incredibly tender which is a big plus. So far the front runner in all of my stew recipe testing is Jacques Pepin's beef in red wine (Food and Wine's website carries the recipe). It packs more flavor punch per bite than this particular recipe. I first tried this stew as the recipe calls. Too soupy for my taste. I then tried thickening it by pureeing the vegetables as other reviewers suggested. It did thicken the sauce but gave it a strange texture. Nobody who tastes this dish will say it's a bad dish. It's a perfectly good dish. Just not THE great stew I'm searching for. That being said, anybody would be happy if you served this to them on a cold day with a nice crusty baguette.

