I made this stew for Christmas Eve dinner and the entire family was ranting and raving about it! The wine and balsamic combination is delicious and the meat tender and flavorful. I also added peas and mushrooms at the end, as well as a pinch of cayenne pepper for just a little kick. Paired with a crunchy loaf of french bread, this is a perfect meal. I can't wait for the leftovers today!

Rating: 4
I got rave reviews on this stew. Having non-gluten needs in the family, it was a perfect recipe. I browned the meat really well, which helped give the broth the richness one expects from stew. I tossed 12 shallots in with the carrots and potatoes and thickened the broth at the end. The broth was such a hit that we needed more, so I added beef stock and red wine and simmered what was left before storing it. I like the idea of chipotle peppers to add a kick, and might use some in adobo sauce next time. My foodie kids want the recipe!

Rating: 3
This was a good, easy recipe. I added a few additional ingredients to give it a little zip. First I dredged the meat in flour to which I added salt, pepper & cayenne, since many reviewers said the sauce was too thin. I also threw in a few extra herbs. Finally, I added petite boiler onions that I browned in butter and small pieces of bacon when the carrots and potatoes went in. To thicken I added flour mixed with butter at the very end. It was yummy the first night, but really looking forward to the leftovers. With my addditions, I'd give it four forks!

