Rating: 4
This is an excellent recipe as is. The beauty of it is it can be made the day ahead before serving. Having said that, one could make modifications to the recipe to really elevate this dish. You can take the elements: The meat braised in liquid (and I prefer more wine, broth and very little salt at this point) The liquid itself, the potatoes and the carrots. Not including the carrots you have used in the sauce which is strained, the carrots and the potatoes you serve with this can be done separately by steaming them ( You will need two steamers) Baby carrots are charming, and potatoes in nice ovals are very classic. The sauce is further reduced, and a roux can be made to thicken (not too much flour!) With the roux you would take butter on heat and add a bit of flour to expand, not too high of heat, then slowly add liquid and whisk and continue adding in a slow stream to get the consistancy desired. Should not be gummy, but not thin. In presentation you have the sauce placed first on the plate( not too much), then the meat, with some sauced bathed over, then the potato ovals and carrots placed on the side. A sprig of thyme, and finely chopped parsley finishes it. I like all kinds of stews, but this method I have found is the cleanest and brightest in flavor. I would caution that you cannot add the potatoes to the braising liquid and then expect to do the type of reduction method I have shown as when the potatoes break down in the sauce, it doe=s not really lend itself to this kind a reduction. All methods are great in their own way!

